<br>
In multi-player RPG's (whether it's online or table-top), you have to pick your companions carefully or develop blinders.<br>
<br>
Obviously in Everquest, you can't pick your fellow players carefully so that everyone around you plays with the same style. You have to roleplay (or fail to do so) with the people available.<br>
<br>
Therefore, you MUST &quot;develop blinders&quot;. By develop blinders, I mean you have to turn a blind eye towards many of the ooc game mechanics and ooc behavior of other players.<br>
<br>
Heck, there are lots of things in the world of Norrath that just plain don't make sense. Big things. HUGE things! For instance, you kill a monster and new ones pop into existence in the same spot. This obviously has nothing ot do with any normal type of reality. Heck, the fact that a 50th level can walk into a WC camp full of orcs and cut them down one by one without them scattering in terror is also silly. BUT, we suspend belief!<br>
<br>
Shintou, you must extend that suspension of belief to the other live players around you, or you will simply never be satisfied. You've created an ideal that even Don Quixote wouldn't try and charge.<br>
<br>
When you see another live player, I love the fact that you try to interract with them in character! But if they are not interested, you have to put them out of your mind. You can not let them disrupt your illusion. If you must &quot;acknowledge&quot; their existence, then Shintou should make up explanations for their behavior, not try to change their behavior.<br>
<br>
For instance, if I was an aggressive elitist DE and walked into that situation... I would have wondered if maybe the bard was being fattened for later slaughter, or maybe he was simply a slave being used to harvest lizard meat for his master. I would have ignored the wood elf completely (wood elves being contemptible and weak) and would have said something like, &quot;How's that young slave working out for you?&quot; to the dark elf.<br>
<br>
Maybe the two would have wanted to roleplay and would have started a dialogue with me, if so..great fun. If not, I would have mentally written them off as a couple of inferior weaklings not worthy of my notice and gone about my business.<br>
<br>
I would NOT try to badger them into playing the roles I think they should play (or any roles whatsoever for that matter). I would NOT let them break my illusions and interfere with my roleplaying mood. If they started to, I would simply /ignore them and go about my business as if they were beneath my notice.<br>
<br>
That's how &quot;I&quot; would handle that situation if I were you. If you continue to let others dictate whether you can successfully stay in character while on FV, you will continue to be disappointed. Just like you ignore the thousands of game mechanics inconsistancies in Norrath, you must ignore the RP inconsistancies in other players...otherwise, you'll never maintain the illusion of being Shintou. <p>Grimwyrd Storm<BR>
(Lux Aeternam)<BR>
31st Human Druid of Karana<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvinckthepaladin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vinck the Paladin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/18/02 2:44:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=249.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: agreement</span><hr size=1> Shintou,<br>
